This is what will happen when the Federal Reserve raises the interest rate.
The interest rate will rise and the bull market will stumble, bond yields will rise and the economy will go into recession.
That's what we know.
What we don’t know is how long it will happen and how long it will take.
In economics, history offers few clues about time frames.
After the first rate hike, the recession occurred in just 11 months and lasted 86 months.
The Federal Reserve’s aggressiveness to raise interest rates is often, though not always, a determining factor in how it responds to the economy and financial assets.
That is why US central bank officials have so strongly stressed that investors should not focus on when the interest rate starts to rise but on the trajectory of the time needed for normalization.
Indeed, there are multiple variables in play.
But ultimately, market players might find that all the turmoil related to the interest rate hike has been exaggerated.
“The Fed’s first rate hike after the global financial crisis will inevitably be interpreted by some as a sign of the era of ‘cheap money,’” Julian Jessop, chief economist at Capital Economics, said in a note to clients.
On the contrary, we do not expect the gradual return of US interest rates to more normal but still low levels to be the seismic shock that everyone seems to fear.
However, it cannot be said that there will be no effects.
Below we present how some sectors of the economy might react, based on historical trends:
Given the situation that the market has faced in recent months, anticipating an increase in the interest rate may volatilize things for a while.
However, at the time of growth, the impact is not so dramatic.
“There appears to be a trend for capital returns to stagnate for 12 to 24 months after the first increase, which may again reflect the monetary policy lag,” Deutsche Bank analysts said in a recent study on what will happen after the Fed’s increases.
Specifically, in the last 35 years, the market has grown sharply - by about 14 percent - heading towards the increase in interest rate, quite unchanged in the period of 250 days after (average rise of 2.6%) after which it returns to normal after 500 days, with an average return in the last six cycles of 14.4%, according to a recent analysis published on Barron by Nuve Management by Stratef.
Deutsche said the impact on stocks tends to become more pronounced later in the interest rate hike cycle and profits are starting to fall.
Recession is a reality of economic life, but rising interest rates often contribute to it.
In the current situation, the Fed is facing conditions that have not existed before and that could accelerate a recession.
Specifically, the gross domestic product will approach its historic low for an increase in the Fed interest rate.
According to Deutsche Bank, of the 118 interest rate increases since 1950, only twice the nominal GDP was less than 4.5%.
Even though in the second quarter of 2015 the figure was 3.6%, few expect the situation to persist, with the third quarter reaching only 1.5%, according to the Atlanta Fed.
Rising interest rates in such a fragile economy could be risky and could raise the question “if this time is different,” Deutsche said.
Players in the market have been preparing for a year-round increase decision by the Fed, with all eyes set on this week’s meeting of the Federal Open Market Commission, which ends on Thursday.
While many strategists and economists believe the FOMC could approve an interest rate increase at the meeting, forward trades indicate a likelihood of only 25%.
“In our study since 1950, all interest rate growth cycles to date have been in a super profit growth cycle, with GDP overshadowing pre-recession peaks very quickly after recovery began,” the report said.
On the contrary, this was a strangely slow recovery after the worst recession of the period under review.
The current cycle is by far the longest expected by the Fed since the end of the last recession; the record had been 35 months, and it has reached 74 months and continues.
Fixed income was also volatile given that the market anticipates an increase in the interest rate and the pattern is somewhat similar to that of dividends.
The main difference is that the impact is faster on bonds than on stocks when the Fed changes the policy.
In the case of bonds, the benefits seem to change direction as soon as the first increase/decrease in the cycle occurs.
At the end of the interest rate growth cycle, the yield on bonds drops immediately," Deutsche said.
Charles Schwab strategists believe that these interest rate hikes will bring profitability closer between short-term and long-term bonds, flattening the curve.
High-yield bonds perform better in such an environment, although “we are still cautious about forcing profitability,” Kathy Jones, a fixed income analyst at Schwab, said in an analysis.
Interestingly, Jones believes that markets have already adapted to Fed policy expectations.
“In addition to the strength of the dollar and declining inflation estimates, there are some signs that the market has adapted to the prospect of a more rigorous monetary policy,” Jones wrote.
Short-term interest rates have risen, the yield curve is more straightforward, the spread of the average credit interest rate has widened and volatility has increased – all market characteristics as the Fed tightens policy.
Broadly speaking, companies operating mostly in the U.S. will benefit from rising interest rates and local products will become more attractive.
