Advantages and Disadvantages of Converting Credits to Swiss Francs
On the banking market, there have already been two offers to convert loans in Swiss francs into lei, the main advantages being the exclusion of currency risk and the reduction of rates.
Disadvantages can come in a few years, when variable interest rates can lead to higher rates.
Banca Transilvania has just completed the process on the conversion of loans in francs granted by Volksbank, and Bancpost announced the conversion offer for its own clients.
According to data compiled by analysts of the FinZoom financial portal, Bancpost offers three years of fixed interest at 1.5%, the lowest on the market.
On the other hand, the conversion offer of Banca Transilvania was accepted by 83% of clients with loans in francs due to two successive reductions: the balance was reduced with the value of the risk and administration fees paid by the client, then an additional reduction of 22.5% was applied to the balance in lei.
Both offers reduce the rates of their own customers, compared to the equivalent monthly plateau in lei before conversion.
Thus, Banca Transilvania reduces the rate by 42.5%, and Bancpost, by 33% in the first three years and, theoretically, by 18% in the following years.
Advantages
The main advantage of the RON credits in CHF is that the currency risk is eliminated, the consumer is protected from future increases of the franc, and the repayment of the credit will be made in the currency in which he collects his salary.
Another major advantage of both conversion offers is that there is no revaluation of the property, no additional guarantees and no further proof of income.
Basically, there will be no new financial and legal analysis of the credit, nor will there be any additional costs as in the case of a refinancing.
Also, both banks offer discount to the monthly rate, compared to the plateau customers before the conversion, equivalent in lei.
Risks
The problem is that the rate in the first few years is made up more of interest, and the customer pays very little back on the principal.
The Bancpost offer with very low interest rates in the first three years seems advantageous for customers.
It is not known how this will evolve after three years.
The margin offered to customers can be more than 3.25%, so in total, and the cost reduction is less.
A possible risk for all variable-interest RON loans is that the ROBOR index will rise significantly in the coming years (more than the Libor index - CHF).
For example, three-month ROBOR is now 1.44%, but in 2013 it had reached 6%, in 2009, over 15%, and in a few days in 2008 it exceeded 40%!
In addition, it is possible to incur other costs, not mentioned in the initial offer.
