For me, the organization of concerts, festivals, tours, the release of albums, all are formidable, extraordinary, but as long as they are in the service of music.
If not, we are in a system where creativity suffers, it no longer has freedom.
To illustrate this phenomenon, David Grimal gave an example of Romanian products before and after accession to the European Union: "In Romania, before you entered the EU, you had good vegetables and meat".
To enter the EU you had to pass health laws that are not good for vegetables and meat.
Production and agriculture are at the service of supermarkets, as is the case in France.
Music is the same, it’s the same logic.
Les Dissonances make tomatoes maybe not too beautiful, but when we cut them they are real tomatoes.
In an ideal world, this music should return to the center and the institutions and industries that manage this system understand that music does not need to be sold, but it needs to be shared, and this can be done starting with educational policy.
“If we were to consider – as do Koreans, Chinese, Japanese – that Western music is one of the most beautiful things of humanity, we would reintroduce its learning in school, we would reintroduce concerts on television and through this education we would no longer need to sell musical by-products,” Grimal believes.
Certainly, there are things in classical music education that remain very communist, that everywhere, is something very militarized.
It depends on this discipline if we compare a musician to a soldier, or if we train a musician who will play an instrument, being, above all, a musician.
We are talking about a completely different education, if we want to form a soldier, it has to be in a way, if we want to form a musician, it is quite another.
What do you think is more dangerous, a soldier or a musician?” the French artist asked, smiling.
Grimal points out that, for artists, the reward of another way of making music comes precisely from overcoming this status of "soldier", overcoming what "they think are their limits": "Musicians discover at a certain moment that they are not soldiers, and therefore after the concert they come out smiling".
David Grimal spoke about his musical project and his vision of music and the artist at the "Festival of Ideas", a discussion with the public organized at the George Enescu International Festival by the Aspen Institute Romania.
Profile David Grimal
After following the Conservatoire National Supérieur de Musique in Paris under the guidance of Regis Pasquier, during which he received advice and encouragement from renowned artists such as Schlomo Mintz and Isaac Stern, David Grimal studied for a year at the Ecole des Sciences Politiques in Paris before meeting Philippe Hirshhorn, who changed the course of his life.
David Grimal has an international career as a solo violinist, along which he has regularly given concerts in the last 20 years on the main classical music scenes of the world and with prestigious orchestras such as Orchestre de Paris, Orchestre Philharmonique de Radio France, Russian National Orchestra, Orchestre National de Lyon, Chamber Orchestra of Europe, Berliner Symphony Orchestra.
He was the recipient of works with dedication from several composers, including Marc-Andre Dalbavie, Brice Pauset, Thierry Escaich, Jean-Francois Zygel, Alexander Gasparov, Victor Kissine, Fuminori Tanada, Richard Dubugnon, Ivan Fedele, Philippe Harrowing, Anders Hillborg, Oscar Bianchi and Conneresson.
In addition to his career as a solo artist, David Grimal wanted to explore more personal projects.
The freedom offered by his collaboration with Les Dissonances allowed him to develop his inner universe by venturing into repertoires that are not accessible to solo artists.
Alongside Les Dissonances, he founded "L'Autre Saison", a series of concerts given for the benefit and together with the homeless at the church of Saint-Leu, located in the heart of Paris.
Since 2008, David Grimal has been a Resident Artist at the Opera in Dijon.
He teaches violin at the Musikhochschule in Saarbrücken, Germany.
He also holds many master classes and was a member of the jury of the International Long-Thibaud Competition in Paris in 2010.
He was awarded the Chevalier des Arts et des Lettres by the French Minister of Culture in 2008.
David Grimal plays on a Stradivarius, "former Roederer" from 1710, but also on "Don Quixote", a violin designed for him by the French luthier Jacques Fustier.
David Grimal was present on Sunday at this year’s George Enescu International Festival together with the Les Dissonances Orchestra, in the program being Debussy, Enescu and Beethoven.
Les Dissonances also took to the stage on Monday, this time with cellist Xavier Phillips in the foreground, and the program was composed of Schnittke, Enescu and Brahms.
