On the occasion of the most anticipated meeting in recent years, Federal Reserve policymakers will spend two days this week around a 27-foot Honduran mahogany table to decide if the time has come to raise a key interest rate for the first time in nearly a decade.
Above them, at one end of the central bank meeting room, will be seen a mural of the United States.
The map is meant to remind Janet L. Yellen, Fed President, and her colleagues to put the nation’s economic interests above all else.
The Central Bank has been given a dual task by Congress: to maximize the U.S. employment rate and maintain price stability.
But since the great economic crisis, Fed leaders have confirmed that there is a third unwritten task: financial stability.
And this third task could be factor X in an overly difficult decision to anticipate, to be announced on Tuesday, that will determine whether the U.S. economy is ready to be rid of the unprecedented stimulus offered by the near-zero short-term interest rate in effect since the end of 2008.
Even though most of the data points to a strong growing economy, recent turmoil in global financial markets could scare already cautious Fed officials off adding volatility by raising the benchmark rate to federal funds — even by just a quarter percentage point.
“Obviously, the labor market and inflation will be the first and main issues they will pursue,” said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist at brokerage firm Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
“But I think if they were looking for an excuse not to raise the interest rate, the growing uncertainty in the global market is enough to give them arguments to wait,” she said.
There is no consensus on the Fed’s decision, which in itself causes instability in the financial market.
About half of economists recently surveyed by Bloomberg anticipated an increase in interest rates this week.
But financial markets expect the Fed to delay, with a key indicator showing the likelihood of growth at only 30 percent.
This would indicate a fall on the stock market if the Fed raises the interest rate, unless policymakers ease the blow by promising it would take a long time for the next rise.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 228.89 points, or 1.4%, to 16,599.85.
The upturn was triggered by expectations that the Fed's policymakers would keep the interest rate stable this week, said John Lonski, chief economist at Moody's Capital Markets Research Group.
“It would be surprising for the Fed to raise the interest rate at this time,” Lonski said.
If the Fed were to do so, “they would have to act in depth in their policies to avoid panic in the financial markets.”
Other experts said an interest rate hike would calm financial markets as it would remove uncertainty about when the Fed will act.
Just a month ago, the Fed appeared to be on track to raise the rate by 0.25% this month, the first small step toward slowing monetary conditions that would confirm the strength of the U.S. recovery.
Yellen said in the spring and early summer that she expected an increase in interest rates this year despite objections by liberals that more economic progress would be needed.
Although job creation slowed in August, labour market growth was solid this year.
The unemployment rate fell to 5.1% last month, the lowest in more than seven years and close to the level the Fed considers total employment.
Earnings showed signs of growth.
And while inflation continued to fall short of the central bank’s annual target, Fed policymakers said a key reason was the temporary effect of sharply falling oil prices.
The economy “can cope with higher rates and needs them given the strain on the labor market,” said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
But global financial markets began fibrillation at the end of this month after China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones industrial average fell 16% below the record high reached in May as investors feared the slowdown in China's economy would pull down global growth.
The market has receded somewhat this month, with the Dow index now about 10% below its May high.
For Fed policymakers, market turmoil adds to the complex calculation of the moment when the interest rate rises.
“Without what has happened in the financial markets and the news of China’s weakening economy in recent weeks, they would be firmer at the hearing,” said Stephen D. Oliner, an experienced researcher at the UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former Fed official.
Now, he predicts that they will wait at least a month to better manage the effects.
“There’s a lot of uncertainty about what the impact will be on the U.S. economy and they almost have no data to rely on after the events in China,” Oliner said.
The well-being of the global economy is not one of the Fed’s major interests, so it should practically not be taken into account when making decisions.
But in reality, the Fed has become the global monetary authority.
In recent years, the central bank’s influence has been enormous.
The mere suggestion by then-president Ben S. Bernanke in 2013 that the Fed could “narrow” its monetary expansion triggered an earthquake in global markets.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly twinned, Fed officials are expected to not only monitor progress in other areas, but also consult with other central banks and experts to better interpret the world economy.
His decision-making process is “more art than science,” said Zachary Karabell, head of global strategy at welfare management firm Envestnet Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, chairman of the Federal Reserve Bank in Richmond, Va., said this month that “the Fed has an oversized track record of reacting to changes in the financial market that seem unrelated to the economic underpinnings.”
Lacker, a voting member of the Federal Open Market Commission, a decision-making body that supported interest rate increases, gave the 1998-99 decisions as an example.
A financial crisis that hit Asia prompted the Fed to cut the benchmark rate by 0.75 percent in three meetings, “despite implications with limited identification for U.S. development,” Lacker said.
A year later, Fed officials reverted to those declines.
The Fed should only put the issue of financial stability first in the event of a major crisis, such as the 2008 market earthquake, said Adam S. Posen, a former member of the Bank of England’s interest rate committee.
The last turbulent period does not even rise to that level, he said.
“We certainly don’t want to get into the situation of fearing an increase in interest rates because the markets are upset,” said Posen, president of the Peterson Institute for International Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act still holds the dual mandate and does not mention financial stability and, until something changes in this regard, I do not think it should take premature action.
