Weight-reduction surgery may be helpful for diabetics with mild obesity
The benefits of weight-loss surgery in people with mild obesity with type 2 diabetes could hold for at least five years, according to a new study.
It is still premature to say whether diabetics with mild obesity live longer after weight loss surgery than those following non-surgical treatments.
“It takes a long time to centralize mortality data,” said Dr. Robin Blackstone, a specialist in obesity surgery, who wrote an article about the new study in JAMA Surgery.
Weight loss operations, also called bariatric surgery, use various methods to shrink the stomach.
They reduce the feeling of hunger and limit the body’s ability to absorb food.
Over the years, bariatric surgery has proven effective in the treatment of type 2 diabetes, but most studies have been conducted on people with morbid obesity, with a body mass index (BMI) of 35 or higher.
BMI, a unit of weight relative to height, is considered normal in the range 18.5-24.9.
A BMI of at least 25 indicates that a person is overweight and people with a BMI over 30 are considered obese.
You can calculate your BMI by going to: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For the new study, researchers at Taiwan’s Min-Sheng General Hospital used data collected after 2007 in a trial comparing two types of bariatric surgery — gastric bypass and sleeve gastrectomy — in the medical treatment of type 2 diabetes in people with mild obesity.
The average BMI in people who underwent surgery decreased from 31 to 24.5 by the end of the fifth year in the study.
Meanwhile, BMI in people who received non-surgical treatments for diabetes remained at almost the same level, namely 29.
Of those who underwent surgery, diabetes was completely cured at 36 percent and partially cured at 28 percent.
In the medically treated group, by comparison, diabetes completely cured in only 1% and partially in only 2% of the subjects.
In addition, blood pressure control, triglycerides and “bad” LDL cholesterol “were generally better in the surgical group,” the authors concluded.
The researchers also monitored blood levels of hemoglobin A1c, which reflects blood glucose levels over time.
The researchers write that the optimum level of hemoglobin A1c is below 7%.
After surgery, the mean haemoglobin A1c level decreased from approximately 9% to approximately 6%.
However, in the group treated by medical methods, it was maintained at about 8%.
But this improved “glycemic control”—reflected by improved levels of hemoglobin A1c—did not reduce the mortality rate to five years, according to lead researcher Dr. Chih-Cheng Hsu and colleagues.
The research team also compared the average results associated with the two types of surgery.
In the fifth year, compared to the sleeve gastrectomy group, the bypass surgery group lost more weight (18.7 versus 14.2 kg), experienced more significant decreases in BMI (7.4 versus 5.1) and haemoglobin A1c 16 % (3.1% versus 2.1%) and had a higher likelihood of remission (diabetes 46 % versus 5.1).
Although the new study does not indicate a benefit in survival or surgery after five years, there is evidence from a study of heavyweight people in Sweden that surgery prolongs life, says Blackstone, from the University of Arizona, Phoenix School of Medicine.
In the Swedish study, obese people who underwent bariatric surgery had an approximately 29% lower chance of dying after 15 years, compared with a group who tried more conventional methods.
Although the new study did not indicate a survival benefit in patients who underwent surgery, Blackstone said it is an optimistic aspect for people with BMI below 35 interested in the procedure.
“This is the point where this paper is critical because it states that this surgery is safe in the group with lower BMI,” without increasing the risk of death or kidney disease, she says.
Blackstone added that patients and their doctors should start taking their weight seriously then the patient’s BMI reaches 27-30.
“I think we’re waiting too long to urge people to take this seriously,” she said.
I think once they've accumulated these genetic changes that have short-circuited their bodies predisposing them to obesity and diabetes, it's extremely hard to get back to normal.
