Fourfold increase in the number of children who have ingested hand detergent in the last 4 years
According to the Georgia Anti-Poison Center, U.S. anti-poison centers reported an increase of about 400% since 2010 in the number of children under the age of 12 who swallowed high-alcohol hand detergent.
According to Dr. Gaylord Lopez, director of the Georgia Anti-Poison Center, cases of hand detergent ingestion in children under the age of 12 reported at anti-poison centers rose from 3,266 in 2010 to 16,117 in 2014.
“Children have more frequent access to these products, and unfortunately a percentage of them end up in the emergency room,” Lopez told CNN.
Lopez said some children intentionally drink detergent and others do so to impress their friends or to respond to challenges on social media.
You can watch movies on YouTube that show teenagers drinking detergent to create cheap drinks.
It turns out that teenagers mixed the detergent with mouthwash with alcohol to get a stronger drink.
Younger children may be attracted to the attractive smell of detergent.
“A child doesn’t think it’s hurting them,” Lopez says.
Many of the most attractive types (hand detergent) are the fragrant ones.
Hand detergents with the flavor of strawberry, grape, orange are the most attractive for children.
Hand detergent contains about 45-95% alcohol.
Especially in young children, just a few swallows can cause alcohol poisoning.
“It’s very concentrated alcohol,” Dr. Stephen Thornton, medical director of the Kansas University Hospital’s poison control center, told Fox 4 in Kansas City.
Thus, we avoid leaving a glass of whiskey on the table, but people leave these hand detergents in accessible places and if the little ones reach them, this is a quick way to consume a lot of alcohol.
Nhaijah Russell, a six-year-old girl who recently ingested the equivalent of four strawberry-flavored hand detergent sprays at school, arrived at the emergency room for treatment.
She had high blood alcohol levels, twice the threshold at which an adult is legally considered under the influence of alcohol, according to Dr. Chris Ritchey, an emergency room doctor who treated her at Gwinnett Medical Center outside Atlanta.
Nhaijah was mumbling and could not walk when he arrived at the emergency room.
Doctors monitored her overnight in a separate children’s hospital to identify signs of brain damage as the girl fell and hit her head from alcohol, Ritchey said.
“It was scary,” Nhaijah’s mother, Ortoria Scott, told CNN.
It could have been fatal.
Lopez advised parents and teachers to use non-alcoholic products or damp wipes and to keep the hand detergent out of the reach of children.
In addition to alcohol poisoning, some detergents have been associated with deaths.
In 2013, two Ontario women died after swallowing hand detergent that contained an undeclared toxic ingredient.
Health authorities assumed that the product contained methanol, a lethal substance, and not ethyl alcohol, specified as an active ingredient.
In January, three fourth-grade students in northern New York plotted to poison their “bad” teacher by “putting antibacterial products in the classroom,” according to a police report.
The teacher is very allergic to hand detergent and banned it in her classroom.
Police said the plan was “insignificant” and referred the disciplinary issue to the school inspectorate.
