The rare disease a man suffers from
American Nick Hess was suspected by his family to be an alcoholic, his wife even filming him when he was dizzy, he could barely stand up and his words were hard to understand.
Although the 35-year-old said he did not drink alcohol, it was obvious that he was drunk.
When she first accused me of being drunk without a drink, I thought she was crazy.
“But friends and family thought, ‘Maybe he’s drinking alone, he’s an alcoholic in secret,’” he said.
When he saw his wife’s footage with him, the Columbus, Ohio, man simply didn’t recognize himself: “I was looking into my eyes and I wasn’t there.”
"It was awful, I didn't remember anything."
In addition, his wife, who, although she doubted him for a while, eventually went with him to countless doctors, remembers that Nick’s breath smelled of alcohol.
The moment that made Nick think the most was when, after a minor accident, when he was hit by another car, it was discovered that he had a blood alcohol content three times above the legal threshold, although the night before he had consumed only one beer.
After years and countless investigations, it was discovered that Nick suffers from an extremely rare disease, "Auto-brewery syndrome".
Basically, his body makes all the carbohydrates consumed ferment, turning into alcohol.
The one who suspected this might be Nick's illness was his wife.
The disease hasn’t had a cure yet, but since giving up carbs, Nick hasn’t had such episodes.
