The government on Wednesday approved the "National Strategy on Immigration for 2015-2018" and the "Action Plan for the current year", documents considered to be "another stage that Romania is undergoing as part of efforts to modernize the process of managing immigration on national territory", according to a press release.
The strategy aims to effectively manage the phenomenon of immigration, including general strategic objectives, specific objectives and directions of action that reflect the policies established at European level, adapted to national realities.
In view of the problems faced by the states in the immediate vicinity of Romania, measures are being considered for the unified and coherent management of situations determined by the possible emergence of an influx of illegal immigrants on the territory of Romania, generated by crisis situations of a political, social, economic or military nature.
“Romanian authorities will contribute to the creation of a flexible admission system, but at the same time, they will pay special attention to citizens from countries with potential migration or that may harm national security,” the source added.
The strategy identifies a number of factors that can influence immigration and asylum, including maintaining the conflict situation in Syria, reactivating the conflict in Iraq, maintaining an unstable situation in areas adjacent to Romania (Ukraine, Transnistria), perpetuating and increasing the intensity of the Israeli-Palestinian armed conflict.
On the other hand, the document also sets some general strategic objectives related to immigration, such as: promoting legal migration, more rigorous controls of the legality of the stay of third-country nationals on the territory of Romania and the corresponding application of removal measures and restrictive measures, improving the national asylum system.
The national strategy shall also include specific objectives relevant to the transposition and implementation of the overall strategic objectives.
These include: facilitating the access to the territory of Romania of third-party citizens who respond to the employment needs, favoring the access of third-party citizens to higher education institutions in Romania for the areas and professions identified as deficient.
Regarding the 2015 Action Plan, the Government considers that it represents "a means by which concrete activities are established that lead to the creation of a flexible system to stop the growing phenomenon of migration".
Romania, in a European top regarding the labor market
Latvia, Romania and Bulgaria recorded the largest increase in total labour costs among the European Union member states in the second quarter of the year, compared to the same period in 2014, according to data published on Wednesday by the European Statistical Office (Eurostat).
The index refers to employers’ staff costs.
Thus, between April and June 2015, the total cost of labour rose by 1.9% in the European Union and by 1.6% in the euro area.
Romania, third in the EU to increase the cost of labor
The highest increases were reported in Latvia (7.9%), Romania (7.7%), Bulgaria (6.8%), Estonia (5.5%) and Lithuania (4.3%).
The only EU countries where the hourly cost of labour fell in the second quarter of this year were Greece (minus 2.9%), Cyprus (minus 1.2%) and Italy (minus 0.4%).
The advance in labor costs in Romania between April and June 2015 is mainly due to the increase in the hourly cost of labor in industry and services, by 7.9% and 7.6%, respectively.
In the construction sector, Romania recorded a 5.8% advance in the hourly cost of labour.
