Few give Jeremy Corbyn a real chance to ever become prime minister.
In the early 1980s another radical leftist leader, Michael Foot, who was not as extreme in convictions as the new party leader, failed miserably in the election.
And at that time there was still a relatively consistent and structured working class in Britain, in the classical sense of the word.
And the unions were sensitively more influential than they are now.
In the new industrial landscape, where services dominate the workforce as a whole, and extensive automation has made the industry massively need high-skilled workforce, Corbyn’s rhetoric has a limited appeal.
But even from the opposition, it can influence important developments that can directly affect us.
In its latest issue, the Financial Times considers that Corbyn’s election increases the chances of Brexit, i.e. Britain’s exit from the EU.
The new Labour leader was a consistent opponent of the country's membership of the Union.
In the eyes of the radical left, Brussels is the agent of international capitalism and a promoter of globalization that imposed austerity on the poor.
When you combine these kinds of ideas with those expressed by the radical right, with anti-immigration rhetoric and you look at the refugee crisis shaking from the foundations of the EU, you end up with an explosive mix.
