It is true, the British business environment, the City, are strong advocates of the country’s stay in the EU.
But today’s Europe is no longer the same as it was in the past.
There are many resentments, which increase in intensity even in these weeks.
The problem is that Brussels, we even had a sample recently in Jean Clude Junker’s speech, increasingly tends to make major decisions over the heads of the vast majority of Member States by consulting only a few European powers, mainly Germany.
And this is happening as the electoral support for anti-system, anti-immigration groups that are at the same time Eurosceptic grows spectacularly across the continent.
In other words, the negatively charged emotional climate has reached higher odds than ever in the past.
Hence the conclusion that the Financial Times draws when evaluating the chances of Brexit.
The pro-EU option is based on a cold calculation that starts from the national interest.
If voters make the brain decision, then the UK will remain in the EU.
But Corbyn’s victory reminds us of the power of emotion in today’s politics.
However, Eastern Europe can be significantly affected by such major developments.
Especially if, as expected, we see a more pronounced integration of the Eurozone, which will push most of the states in the region to the periphery of interest and to that of the decision-making process in Europe.
Corbyn, Tsipras and Syriza in Greece, Podemos in Spain, even Bernie Sanders in the United States feeds his populist rhetoric from the frustrations accumulated in Western societies.
Due to economic and demographic causes, the prosperity enjoyed in the last decades, the generous social benefits, can not continue the same in the years to come.
Under the explosive pressure of the dual crisis, the Eurozone - immigration, both provoked by hasty decisions that have taken into account only integrationist political ambitions, not the ability and willingness of the peoples and governments of Europe to respond to such challenges, the turbulences on the continent, the internal tensions in the EU will increase in intensity and can greatly affect the situation of Romania.
And it's hard to rule out anything from the perspective of possible scenarios.
The question is whether our main political leaders are able to cope with such complicated situations.
